\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 For best results, all staves in a document (with the exception of certain editorial staves such as ossia and solo parts) should be the same height.  Calliope specifies the staff height with the Staff Height aspect of the Document Preferences panel:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_13.tiff \width3900\height4820
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The default value is rastral number 4, which is a useful size for ensemble music.  Solo parts are often in rastral number 1 or 2, while piano staves are often in rastral number 3.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 To set the staff height in a document to a given rastral number, simply press the desired button, followed by \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 ET\f0 .  Notice that the numerical value of the rastral number will appear in the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 taff Height\f0  field.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 To set the the staff height in a document to any given numerical value, enter the value in the \i0\b0\f1\fs24 S\f1 taff Height\f0  field and press \fs24\f1\b0\i0 S\f1 ET\f0 .  The measurement units are specified using the Page Layout Panel in the way usual for NeXTStep applications. If the entered value is very near to an integral rastral number, then the corresponding rastral button will light up.  Otherwise, none will light up. \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Using a document of your choice, change the staff height to several different values to see the effect on the display.  Use both the rastral number buttons and the staff height field.  Notice that all the musical items, verse underlay and text boxes automatically appear in a size that corresponds to the chosen staff height.   If a given size is too small to read on the screen, you may always increase the magnification using the display scale button in the lower right-hand corner of the document window.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 One consequence of choosing a different staff height is that staves will be able to contain more or fewer musical items.  Choosing higher rastral numbers (that is, smaller staff heights) will mean that more notes may be contained on a staff of the same length.  After choosing a different staff height, you may need to readjust the staves (\fs24\f1\b0\i0 F\f1 ormat\f2\f2 ®\f1\f1 A\f1 djust All in Doc\f0 ) to accommodate the existing notes to the new staff.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Reduced Staff Sizes\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Although all the staves in a document should have the same rastral number, it is useful for editorial or performance purposes to use two additional \i reduced sizes:\i0\i0   75% and 50%.  The normal sized staff, at 100%, is the staff height as specified in the Preferences Panel.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Individual staves of a system may be set also to 75% and 50% of the specified staff height.  The sizes are specified using the System Inspector.  For example, the following system (from the Schötz motet Paratum cor meum) has two violin parts on reduced sized staves:\par
