}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The staff aspect of the System Inspector for staff 1 looks like this:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_15.tiff \width4160\height4680
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\i0 Notice the \i0\fs24\f1\b0 7\f1 5%\f0\i0  selection on the Size buttons.  Staff 2 is also at 75%.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Margins\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The first system of every document contains a Page Format Marker, as identified in previous lessons.  The marker has darkened sides to suggest left and right margins.  Using the document of your choice, Command-click (or double-click) on a page format marker.  You should see the inspector, which looks something like this:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_12.tiff \width3920\height6660
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 All fields are shown in the measurement units specified in the Page Layout Panel, as for all NeXTStep applications. The current measurement unit can also be seen at the bottom of the inspector.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The settings shown on the Inspector take effect on the page on which the marker appears, and remain in effect during all subsequent pages until superceded by another Page Format marker.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Page Margins\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The margins of a typical page are illustrated as follows:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_9.eps \width6520\height5060
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The amounts for each of these margins is specified with the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 L\f1 eft Margin\f0 , \fs24\f1\b0\i0 R\f1 ight Margin\f0 , \fs24\f1\b0\i0 T\f1 op Margin\f0  and \fs24\f1\b0\i0 B\f1 ottom Margin\f0  fields of the Page Format Inspector.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Individual systems may also be indented on the left and right.  This is specified on an individual basis with the System Inspector.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Header and Footer Offsets\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The vertical placement of running headers and footers is specified with the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 H\f1 eader Offset\f0  and \fs24\f1\b0\i0 F\f1 ooter Offset\f0  fields, as illustrated here:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_8.eps \width5000\height4040
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Headers appear with the upper edge of the header's bounding box aligned with the specified header offset. Similarly, footers appear with the lower edge of the footer's bounding box aligned with the specified footer offset.  It is possible to move the offsets to any desired value, but it is wise to confine header and footer text to the margin area.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Binding Margins\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 It is also possible to increase the margin area on the left and right by extra amounts to accommodate binding.  To use binding margins, the left and right margins need not be changed: the left (right) binding margin is specified as an addition to the existing left (right) margin.  If there is no extra binding margin, the fields should be set to 0.  The Inspector allows for different amounts of left and right binding margin to be specified on even- and odd-numbered pages.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_7.eps \width5880\height4680
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 All the margins can be shown in the current document by pressing the \fs24\f1\b0\i0 F\f1 ormat\f2\f2 ®\f1\f1 S\f1 how Margins\f0  command.  Here is an example screenshot in which all the margin lines can be seen:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_18.eps \width8720\height8200
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Notice how the header and footer are aligned against the line specified by the header and footer offset.  The long vertical binding margin line is only seen if the binding margin is greater than 0.  In the above screenshot there is a binding margin line at both sides of the page.  This is not typical practice, but is shown here to illustrate the appearance of the margin display.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa80\li0\ri0\f1\fs32\b1\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Creating a new Page Format\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\i0 There is always a page format marker associated with the first system of a document.  However, if the format is to be changed part way through a document, you need to associate a new page format marker with the system at which the new format is to take effect.  To associate a Page Format Marker with a system, select the system (by clicking on its marker) and press \i0\f1\fs24\b0 S\f1 ystem\f2\f2 ®\f1\f1 N\f1 ew Page Format\f0\i0 .  You will see a new Inspector panel with values inherited from the previous Page Format marker in the document.  You may change the values as desired, then press SET.  Notice that the document repaginates with the system at the top of a new page.  Specifying a new Page Format always begins a new page, to prevent an ambiguity about which page is to appear in which format.  The options for the Page Format Inspector are as follows:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Format Options\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0\i0 The \i0\fs24\f1\b0 F\f1 ormat Options\f0\i0  popup button selects between a number of different ways that systems may be laid out on the page.  For most purposes, the \i0\fs24\f1\b0 D\f1 efault\f0\i0  selection is suitable.  The available options are described below.  Some descriptions may refer to a quantity \i\i S\i0\i0 , which is an optimum inter-system spacing determined automatically by Calliope, but which can be influenced by the Layout Options aspect of the Document Preferences panel.  Basically, \i\i S\i0\i0  is an amount in the range between the `minimum system gap' and the `maximum balance gap' parameters of the Layout Options.  The default values for these parameters are 6\i\i ss\i0\i0  and 12\i\i ss\i0\i0 , respectively.\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Head Aligned\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The top of the first system on the page is aligned with the top margin. Each system is separated by at most \i S\i0 . Any leftover space is at the bottom of the page:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_6.eps \width4320\height3820
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Foot Aligned\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The bottom of the last system on the page is aligned with the bottom margin. Each system is separated by at most \i S\i0 . Any leftover space is at the top of the page:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_5.eps \width4320\height3820
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Spread\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 The top of the first system on the page is aligned with the top margin. Any excess space is divided into \i N\i0  equal parts of amount \i X\i0 , each part following each system:\par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qc\fi0\sb80\sa0\li0\ri0\f0\fs24\b0\i0\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 {{\NeXTGraphic4 graphic_4.eps \width5060\height3820
}¬} \par
\pard\tx1440\tx2880\tx4320\tx5760\qj\keepn\fi0\sb240\sa0\li0\ri0\f1\fs28\b0\i1\ul0\strike0\scaps0\cf0 Balanced\par
